{"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0,"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[],"authorship_tag":"ABX9TyNToJ69rs4740UoNiaFZvQ6"},"kernelspec":{"name":"python3","display_name":"Python 3"},"language_info":{"name":"python"}},"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## **LINEAR** **REGRESSION**\n","\n","**Linear Regression is a type of **Surepvised Learning** Machine learning Algorithm that learns from the labelled datasets and maps the data points with most optimized Linear function which can be used for prrediction on new Data sets.**"],"metadata":{"id":"bsfTnd_Jd9ka"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## **Best-Fit Line**\n","\n","In linear regression the best fit line is the straight line that most accurately represent the relationship between the input and output variable.\n","\n","**Goal Of Fit Line**\n","The goal of the best fit line is to find the a straight line that minimizes the error between the observed data points and the predicted values.\n","\n","**EQUATION OF THE BEST FIT LINE**\n","\n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 182818.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","\n","Best fit line wiil be one that optimizes the value of m(slope) and b(intercept) So that the value of y yemains close to the data points."],"metadata":{"id":"ySUJN6WvnmKo"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## **Minimizing the error: Least Squared Method**\n","The idea behind this method is to minimize the sum of squareed differnce between the actual values and predicted values from the line called  \n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 183114.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","\n","**We have to minimize the Residual.**\n","**To minimize Residual we USE:**\n","\n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 183007.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"ACKA6iAeov9N"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##**TYPES OF LINEAR REGERESSION**\n","\n","1. **SIMPLER LINEAR REGRESSION**\n","\n","   When these is only one Indepenent feature(X) it is known as **Simpler Linear Regression** or **Univariate Linear Regression**.\n","\n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 182329.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","2.  **Multiple Linear Regression**\n","\n","     When there is more than one ondependent feature and only one dependent variable it is known as **Multiple Linear regression** or **Multivariate Linear Regression**\n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 182656.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n"],"metadata":{"id":"YL8mJHldCTEx"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **COST FUNCTION**\n","\n","The cost function measures how far the predicted values(̂y) are from the actual values.\n","\n","It helps identify and reduce errors to find the best fit line.\n","\n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 183804.png](data:image/png;base64,)"],"metadata":{"id":"ivf72ECnHZ9Q"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **GRADIENT DESCENT**\n","Gradient Descent is the **Optimization Technique** used to train a linear regression model by minimizing the prediction error.\n","To minimize the **Cost function** we use **Gradient Descent**\n","\n","![Screenshot 2025-12-15 184214.png](data:image/png;base64,)"],"metadata":{"id":"DxR_uFV0IRVk"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **Evaluation Metrics**\n","\n","\n","\n","1.   **MEAN SQUARED ERROR (MSE)**\n","\n","      MSE is an evaluation metric that calculates the average of the squared differences between the actual and predicted values for all the data points. The difference is squared to ensure that negative and positive differences don't cancel each other out.\n","\n","      ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 185759.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","1.   **MEAN ABSOLUTE ERROR(MAE)**\n","\n","     Mean Absolute Error is an evaluation metric used to calculate the accuracy of a regression model. MAE measures the average absolute difference between the predicted values and actual values.\n","     ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 185935.png](data:image/png;base64,)  \n","2.   **ROOT MEAN SQUARED(RSME)**\n","\n","      RMSE is in the same unit as the target variable and highlights larger errors more clearly.\n","      ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 190238.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","\n","2.   **R-SQUARED**\n","\n","     R-Squared is a statistic that indicates how much variation the developed model can explain or capture. It is always in the range of 0 to 1.\n","\n","     ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 190615.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","5. **Residual Sum of squares/Errors**\n","   \n","   The sum of squares of the residual for each data point in the plot or data is known as the residual sum of squares or RSS.\n","\n","   ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 190934.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","\n","  6. **Total Sum of Sruares**\n","\n","     The sum of the data points' errors from the answer variable's mean is known as the total sum of squares or TSS.\n","\n","     ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 191123.png](data:image/png;base64,)"],"metadata":{"id":"xwKdufqjJS9i"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **REGULARIZATION**\n","\n","\n","\n","1.   **LASSO REGRESSION****(L1 REGULARIZATION)**\n","\n","     Lasso Regression is a technique used for regularizing a linear\n","     regression model, it adds a penalty term to the linear regression objective function to prevent overfitting.\n","     \n","     ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 191547.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","2.   **RIDGE REGRESSION(L2 REGULARIZATION)**\n","\n","     Ridge regression is a linear regression technique that adds a regularization term to the standard linear objective. Again, the goal is to prevent overfitting by penalizing large coefficient in linear regression equation.\n","\n","  ![Screenshot 2025-12-15 191716.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"Gd7ZTONYQJiK"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"8CGJJLYku_36"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# **CAPM MODEL USING LINEAR REGRESSION**\n","\n","**CORE IDEA:**\n","\n","The CAPM (Capital Asset Pricing Model) uses Linear Regression to explain a stock’s returns based on market returns. It models the relationship as:\n","\n","Stock Return = α + β × Market Return + ε,  \n","where β measures sensitivity to market risk and α captures excess return (alpha).Linear regression helps estimate α and β from historical data, making CAPM a fundamental tool in asset pricing and risk assessment.\n","\n","**WHY IT IS IMPORTANT:**\n","\n","CAPM is crucial in the industry because it helps quantify the risk-return tradeoff. It allows analysts, portfolio managers, and risk professionals to:\n","\n","- Estimate expected returns based on systematic risk (beta).  \n","- Assess performance by evaluating alpha (excess return).  \n","\n","It's widely used in portfolio management, asset pricing, cost of capital estimation, and performance benchmarking."],"metadata":{"id":"-r1yI7LGRW3V"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["'''First, We are going to Import all the Important Libraries, Which helps us to fetch market data, visualize our\n","code,Structure our code easily.'''\n","import yfinance as yf\n","import pandas as pd\n","import numpy as np\n","import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n","import seaborn as sns\n","from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression\n","from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score\n","\n","#Download data\n","asset = yf.download(\"RELIANCE.NS\", start=\"2018-01-01\", end=\"2023-12-31\")\n","market = yf.download(\"^NSEI\", start=\"2018-01-01\", end=\"2023-12-31\")"],"metadata":{"id":"0pPGag3enlfh","colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765808779778,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":73,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"outputId":"19e0522a-d150-449f-dfb2-c147deafda53"},"execution_count":124,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stderr","text":["/tmp/ipython-input-1845012887.py:12: FutureWarning: YF.download() has changed argument auto_adjust default to True\n","  asset = yf.download(\"RELIANCE.NS\", start=\"2018-01-01\", end=\"2023-12-31\")\n","[*********************100%***********************]  1 of 1 completed\n","/tmp/ipython-input-1845012887.py:13: FutureWarning: YF.download() has changed argument auto_adjust default to True\n","  market = yf.download(\"^NSEI\", start=\"2018-01-01\", end=\"2023-12-31\")\n","[*********************100%***********************]  1 of 1 completed\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["'''#Fill any missing price data with the most recent available value to avoid errors in calculations\n","and apply Change in percent rather that absolute'''\n","asset['Return'] = asset['Close'].ffill().pct_change()\n","market['Market_Return'] = market['Close'].ffill().pct_change()\n","#Merges the asset and market return data on date index, aligning both series for valid comparison\n","data = pd.merge(asset['Return'], market['Market_Return'], left_index=True, right_index=True)\n","#Drop all the NaN values from the dataset\n","data.dropna(inplace=True)\n","X = data[['Market_Return']]\n","y = data['Return']\n","n = len(data)"],"metadata":{"id":"ci1AoctLVjWW","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765808780338,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":3,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}}},"execution_count":125,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#Applying Linear Regression Algorithm and Calculating Alpha and Beta\n","model = LinearRegression()\n","model.fit(X, y)\n","alpha = model.intercept_\n","beta = model.coef_[0]\n","print(f\"Alpha (Intercept): {alpha:.5f}\")\n","print(f\"Beta (slope): {beta:.5f}\")\n","data['Predicted_Return'] = model.predict(X)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"fGc4ITy9oeGj","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765808974200,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":6,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"outputId":"71aacb83-879f-4730-caa2-774096212eec"},"execution_count":137,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Alpha (Intercept): 0.00033\n","Beta (slope): 1.10958\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#Visualizing Our Linear Regression Model using MatplotLib Library and Seaborn\n","plt.figure(figsize=(5,4))\n","sns.regplot(x='Market_Return', y='Return', data=data, line_kws={'color': 'red'})\n","plt.title('CAPM Regression:RELIANCE vs NIFTY 50')\n","plt.xlabel('Market Return (NIFTY50)')\n","plt.ylabel('RELIANCE Return')\n","plt.grid(False)\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":410},"id":"7KNiR-yBW_6r","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765809049274,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":307,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"outputId":"8fa37f6e-5a85-4a1d-c17b-0ea7c8ea90a7"},"execution_count":138,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 500x400 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#Now Applying Gradient Descent TO IMPROVE THE MODEL\n","def gradient_descent(X, y, lr=0.01, epochs=1000):\n","    alpha = 0\n","    beta = 0\n","\n","    X_np = X.values.flatten()\n","    y_np = y.values\n","    n_samples = len(y_np)\n","\n","    for _ in range(epochs):\n","        y_pred_np = alpha + beta * X_np\n","        error_np = y_np - y_pred_np\n","        d_alpha = -2 * np.sum(error_np) / n_samples\n","        d_beta = -2 * np.sum(error_np * X_np) / n_samples\n","        alpha -= lr * d_alpha\n","        beta -= lr * d_beta\n","\n","    return alpha, beta, pd.Series(y_pred_np, index=y.index)\n","alpha, beta, y_pred_np = gradient_descent(X, y)\n","print(f\"Alpha (intercept): {alpha:.5f}\")\n","print(f\"Beta (slope): {beta:.5f}\")\n"],"metadata":{"id":"ki6H74o799wH","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765809144160,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":20,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"outputId":"d1ca533f-bf65-4e91-c435-aea10f7c4f9c"},"execution_count":142,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Alpha (intercept): 0.00096\n","Beta (slope): 0.00292\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["#Calculating all the Evaluation Metrics\n","mse = mean_squared_error(y, y_pred_np)\n","mae = mean_absolute_error(y, y_pred_np)\n","rmse = np.sqrt(mse)\n","r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred_np)\n","\n","print(\"\\nEvaluation Metrics:\")\n","print(f\"MSE:  {mse:.6f}\")\n","print(f\"MAE:  {mae:.6f}\")\n","print(f\"RMSE: {rmse:.6f}\")\n","print(f\"R²:   {r2:.6f}\")\n","\n","#Now ploting the Model after Applying Gradient Descent\n","plt.scatter(X, y, alpha=0.3, label='Actual')\n","plt.plot(X, y_pred_np, color='red', label='Predicted (CAPM)')\n","plt.xlabel('Market Return(NIFTY50)')\n","plt.ylabel('Stock Return(RELIANCE)')\n","plt.title('CAPM Model using Gradient Descent')\n","plt.legend()\n","plt.show()"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":576},"id":"D6lWwE9x-grK","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765809189041,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":1346,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"outputId":"cae60b0c-e016-44cf-9793-a85967cbe47e"},"execution_count":143,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["\n","Evaluation Metrics:\n","MSE:  0.000353\n","MAE:  0.012957\n","RMSE: 0.018776\n","R²:   0.002408\n"]},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"code","source":[],"metadata":{"id":"VW29F5bLpiag","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765808030891,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":2,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}}},"execution_count":109,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"56176849"},"source":["# Task\n","Next, I will scale the 'Market_Return' feature using `StandardScaler` to normalize its range, which can help the gradient descent algorithm converge more efficiently. After scaling, I'll update the `X` variable with the scaled data.\n","```python\n","from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n","\n","# Initialize StandardScaler\n","scaler = StandardScaler()\n","\n","# Scale the 'Market_Return' feature\n","X_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X)\n","\n","# Update X with the scaled data\n","X = pd.DataFrame(X_scaled, columns=X.columns, index=X.index)\n","\n","print(\"Market_Return feature has been scaled.\")\n","print(X.head())\n","```"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"a2f9b9ab"},"source":["## Analyze Current Gradient Descent Performance\n","\n","### Subtask:\n","Examine the current alpha, beta, and evaluation metrics (MSE, MAE, RMSE, R²) of the gradient descent model to establish a baseline for comparison.\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"47851d9c"},"source":["**Reasoning**:\n","The subtask asks to print the current alpha, beta, and evaluation metrics. These values are already computed and stored in the kernel. I will print them directly.\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"03d16b24","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765809746065,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":14,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"outputId":"65dbac0b-4ca1-45d2-f9ab-47780e859339"},"source":["print(f\"Alpha (intercept) from Gradient Descent: {alpha:.5f}\")\n","print(f\"Beta (slope) from Gradient Descent: {beta:.5f}\")\n","\n","print(\"\\nEvaluation Metrics for Gradient Descent Model:\")\n","print(f\"MSE:  {mse:.6f}\")\n","print(f\"MAE:  {mae:.6f}\")\n","print(f\"RMSE: {rmse:.6f}\")\n","print(f\"R²:   {r2:.6f}\")"],"execution_count":144,"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Alpha (intercept) from Gradient Descent: 0.00096\n","Beta (slope) from Gradient Descent: 0.00292\n","\n","Evaluation Metrics for Gradient Descent Model:\n","MSE:  0.000353\n","MAE:  0.012957\n","RMSE: 0.018776\n","R²:   0.002408\n"]}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"f286a04d"},"source":["## Feature Scaling\n","\n","### Subtask:\n","Scale the 'Market_Return' feature using Standard