terate through different learning rates and epochs, train the model using `gradient_descent`, evaluate its performance, and keep track of the best performing combination of hyperparameters and model parameters. This requires defining the hyperparameter ranges, initializing tracking variables, and then performing the iterative training and evaluation.\n","\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"ad2e2a79","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1765809856897,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":554,"user":{"displayName":"arnav garg","userId":"14589761879025667823"}},"outputId":"70b16c1c-ab48-46fa-8745-392f943444aa"},"source":["from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score\n","import numpy as np\n","\n","# 1. Define lists of learning rates and epochs to test\n","learning_rates = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1]\n","epochs = [500, 1000, 2000]\n","\n","# 2. Initialize variables to store the best MSE and corresponding parameters\n","best_mse = float('inf')\n","best_alpha = None\n","best_beta = None\n","best_lr = None\n","best_epochs = None\n","best_y_pred = None\n","\n","# 3. Create nested loops to iterate through each combination\n","for lr in learning_rates:\n","    for ep in epochs:\n","        print(f\"Testing with Learning Rate: {lr}, Epochs: {ep}\")\n","        # 4. Call the gradient_descent function\n","        current_alpha, current_beta, current_y_pred = gradient_descent(X, y, lr=lr, epochs=ep)\n","\n","        # 5. Calculate the Mean Squared Error (MSE) for the current model's predictions\n","        current_mse = mean_squared_error(y, current_y_pred)\n","\n","        # 6. Compare current MSE with best_mse and update if better\n","        if current_mse < best_mse:\n","            best_mse = current_mse\n","            best_alpha = current_alpha\n","            best_beta = current_beta\n","            best_lr = lr\n","            best_epochs = ep\n","            best_y_pred = current_y_pred\n","\n","# 7