cessing step aids in more efficient model convergence.\n","*   **Optimal Hyperparameters Identified**: Through hyperparameter tuning, the best performing combination was determined to be a learning rate of 0.1 and 500 epochs.\n","*   **Improved Model Performance**: After applying feature scaling and hyperparameter tuning, the gradient descent model's performance significantly improved:\n","    *   Alpha (intercept) remained consistent at 0.00096, while Beta (slope) increased to 0.01273.\n","    *   Mean Squared Error (MSE) decreased by approximately 45.9% from 0.000353 to 0.000191.\n","    *   Mean Absolute Error (MAE) decreased by approximately 25.3% from 0.012957 to 0.009679.\n","    *   Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) decreased by approximately 26.4% from 0.018776 to 0.013830.\n","    *   R-squared (R²) saw a dramatic improvement, increasing from 0.002408 to 0.458791, indicating that the model explains a much larger proportion of the variance in stock returns.\n","*   **Visual Confirmation**: A scatter plot of actual vs. predicted stock returns with the tuned regression line visually confirmed a much better fit to the data after improvements.\n","\n","### Insights or Next Steps\n","*   The substantial improvement in R² from almost zero to 0.458791 highlights the critical role of both feature scaling and hyperparameter tuning in developing a more robust and predictive gradient descent model for financial data.\n","*   Further exploration could involve incorporating additional relevant features (e.g., industry-specific factors, macroeconomic indicators) into the CAPM model, and employing more advanced regularization techniques or alternative optimization algorithms to potentially achieve even better predictive performance and model stability.\n"]}]}